        >
          The agent is an untrusted process.
        </h2>
        <div class="space-y-5 text-base leading-relaxed text-[#a3a3a3]">
          <p>
            For 50 years, software engineering ceremony &mdash; version control,
            code review, blame, audit logs &mdash; assumed one thing: the writer
            of the code is a human you can hold accountable. That assumption
            silently broke when AI agents started writing the majority of new
            code.
          </p>
          <p>
            Agents fail in ways human contributors never would. They silently
            delete tests. They rewrite mocks to make themselves pass. They
            refactor across boundaries without understanding intent. A bad
            decision at 14:32:07 is 200 files deep by 14:32:42. None of the
            tools in your stack &mdash; git, your editor, your CI &mdash; were
            designed for that.
          </p>
          <p class="text-white">
            Treat AI coding agents the way a security engineer treats any
            process with write access to your filesystem: assume it will
            eventually do something wrong, and build the controls that let you
            recover when it does.
          </p>
          <p>
            <code class="text-cyan-300">agent-undo</code> is the substrate. Observability,
            attribution, reversibility &mdash; the three primitives the next decade
            of agent-aware tooling will be built on.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

